  "doc_id": "48271",
  "text": "Ex vivo measurements of clotting, such as the optical ARF method described in this study, almost all suffer a potential limitation in accuracy with regard to inferences of coagulopathies in vivo due to the fact that the blood sample is clotted under quiescent conditions. Since blood clot formation under stasis may increase fibrin and decrease platelet concentration as compared to in vivo arterial clots [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , it is important to qualify interpretations of clot mechanics depending on whether the test is based on quiescent or shear conditions, and additionally how the specific magnitude of shear might influence clotting; i.e., is the shear arterial or venous? With that consideration in mind, static condition measurement techniques, such as optical ARF, may be more appropriate when assessing coagulopathies characterized by venous flows, trauma, or surgical bleeding.",
